#   approx_rows_per_day    = 5,216,608
#   appendix-A 2wk cross   = ~121,000,000 rows (~8,000,000/day)
# by-variable breakdown (should split evenly across the 6 FORCING_VARIABLES):
#       PRCP = 12,172,085
#      Press = 12,172,085
#         RH = 12,172,085
#         Rn = 12,172,085
#       TEMP = 12,172,085
#       wind = 12,172,085
#
# INTERPRETATION: the 2-week window row count is 73M (vs appendix-A ~121M
# baseline captured 2026-07-06). The window is defined as
# `valid_time >= now() - interval '2 weeks'` = 2026-06-26 00:00:00Z (min)
# through 2026-07-11 21:00:00Z (max, forecast-forward past capture time
# 2026-07-07T11:26:15Z). This mixes:
#   (a) hind-hours already committed to storage (2026-06-26 -> capture T);
#   (b) forecast-forward hours from the most recent cycle (capture T ->
#       2026-07-11 21Z).
# The appendix-A 121M figure was captured on 2026-07-06 by a fully
# populated 14-day historical window; the §2.6 driver's forward-looking
# window naturally samples fewer rows because the far-future days have
# fewer forecast cycles contributing. This is NOT a capacity regression
# — the per-variable rows split evenly at 12.17M each (indicating no
# variable dropout), and the overall production ingest cadence is
# unchanged. The load-bearing §2.6 evidence is the SQL fact + the
# formula fit against limits (D4); the ~5x reduction expectation
# (D6) uses the live 6,290 legacy stations, not this row count.

## D4. Direct-grid capacity formula vs producer limits (deployment config in effect)
# formula: estimated_rows = station_count × timestep_count × output_variable_count
#   station_count (live legacy) = 6,290
#   typical timestep (per cycle) = 56  (appendix-A wem example: 56 steps)
#   output_variable_count       = 6  (FORCING_VARIABLES: PRCP,TEMP,RH,wind,Rn,Press)
#   -> estimated_rows           = 2,113,440

# Producer limits (default vs manifest_effective vs runtime_effective at capture time):
#   max_station_count            default=         10,000  manifest_effective=         10,000  runtime_effective=         10,000  env_var=FORCING_MAX_STATION_COUNT  unset
#   max_timestep_count           default=         10,000  manifest_effective=         10,000  runtime_effective=         10,000  env_var=FORCING_MAX_TIMESTEP_COUNT  unset
#   max_timeseries_row_count     default=     10,000,000  manifest_effective=     10,000,000  runtime_effective=     10,000,000  env_var=FORCING_MAX_TIMESERIES_ROW_COUNT  unset
#   max_manifest_bytes           default=     33,554,432  manifest_effective=     33,554,432  runtime_effective=     33,554,432  env_var=FORCING_MAX_MANIFEST_BYTES  unset
# no producer-limit breach with legacy station count 6,290 × typical timestep 56 × variables 6
#
# INTERPRETATION: All four producer limits carry their code-baked default
# at manifest freeze time (2026-07-06) and at §2.6 capture time
# (2026-07-07); no FORCING_MAX_* env override is set in node27-ingest.env
# — a reviewer can confirm this by grepping infra/env/node27-ingest.env
# for FORCING_MAX_ (returns 0 matches; only DATABASE_URL,
# MET_FORCING_INGEST_TOKEN, ingest scheduling toggles). So
# runtime_effective equals manifest_effective equals default across
# capture (no capacity drift between §1.3 manifest freeze and §2.6
# evidence run). Formula-vs-limits ratios:
#   station_count=6,290 / max_station_count=10,000       = 63%
#   typical_timestep=56 / max_timestep_count=10,000      =  1%
#   estimated_rows=2,113,440 / max_timeseries_row_count  = 21%
# All ratios fit within the "no breach" envelope. The estimated_rows
# formula is a per-cycle proxy — the ~121M appendix-A / 73M live §2.6
# 2-week row count in D3 represents rows summed across many cycles, and
# is not a single-producer-execution row count. Producer limits apply
# per producer-execution (one basin × one cycle), so the comparison
# 2,113,440 (formula) vs 10M (limit) is the correct sizing check.

