#   MAX_DIRECT_GRID_FORCING_CSV_BYTES      pinned=      8,388,608 bytes/lines (from manifest, per runtime.py:52-58)
#   MAX_DIRECT_GRID_SP_ATT_BYTES           pinned=     33,554,432 bytes/lines (from manifest, per runtime.py:52-58)
#   MAX_DIRECT_GRID_TSD_FORC_LINES         pinned=        250,000 bytes/lines (from manifest, per runtime.py:52-58)
#   MAX_DIRECT_GRID_FORCING_CSV_LINES      pinned=        250,000 bytes/lines (from manifest, per runtime.py:52-58)
#   MAX_DIRECT_GRID_SP_ATT_LINES           pinned=      2,000,000 bytes/lines (from manifest, per runtime.py:52-58)
#   MAX_DIRECT_GRID_STAGING_LINE_BYTES     pinned=         65,536 bytes/lines (from manifest, per runtime.py:52-58)
# all 7 staging limits are positive integers; manifest not corrupt
#
# CROSS-CHECK: staging-2.5.node-22.pass.log D7 attested that the 3-station
# synth package files all sit well below every one of these 7 limits (max
# file size 1,504 bytes for binding-manifest.json). At production scale
# (largest basin = zhaochen_hhy per staging-2.5 D8: 1,420 stations,
# 7,800 elements), the estimated staging-file sizes are:
#   * .sp.att: ~7,800 element rows × ~30 bytes/row ≈ 234 KB (0.7% of 32 MiB cap)
#   * .tsd.forc: ~1,420 station rows × ~15 bytes/row ≈ 21 KB (0.25% of 8 MiB cap)
#   * per-station CSV: ~56 timestep rows × ~100 bytes/row ≈ 5.6 KB per file
#     (0.07% of 8 MiB cap; 1,420 files at 5.6 KB each = 8 MB total across basin)
# All at least 100x below the 7 pinned limits. Runtime staging headroom
# is enormous even for the largest basin; the 7 constants above are
# hardware-driven safety margins, not tight ceilings on legitimate
# workload.

